I was hoping it would be awesome, I think the food hall concept has a lot of potential, but frankly it’s not great in any regard. The place looks cool, parking is affordable if you get it validated, and it seems like a lively place. Time out is extremely rich in cues suggesting that this is a premium experience with great food, except none of those expectations come to fruition: portions are tiny, prices are high, and food quality is bad compared to what you get in the very same area. You would expect that by centralizing key expenses and cutting out waiters, costs would fall, but it seems prices don’t.  We walked around for a bit and tried to find something worthwhile, we briefly considered getting burgers until we realized $14 got you something approximately the size of a McD’s quarter pounder and no sides. Pizza samples frankly looked like they were pressed in a mold and topped with whatever. I settled on the chicken place and paid $17 for a “spicy chicken and dumpling noodle soup”. Pretty ok broth and noodles, but the “chicken” was literally crumbles of boiled ground chicken. It tasted exactly like the time I put whey protein powder in my ramen bowl before microwaving it, and when it came out the protein had congealed into tasteless chewy globs. My girlfriend paid $12 for “chicken and waffle fries”, which consisted of fatty chicken thighs breaded nearly entirely with cornstarch (gross), and barely crispy fries covered in way too much “syrup”. The menu advertised that it came topped with “umami salt”—make no mistake, that’s just MSG seasoning—and seeing such euphemisms felt like a painful reminder that this hall only seemed invested in giving patrons the impression they were buying fancier food than they were getting.  If you’re into the food hall concept, I’ve had far better experiences at Faneuil Hall, Boston Public Market, or Craft Food Hall

Lunch for 4 ended up being nearly $90 ... and keep in mind there is no table service and you have to fight for your seat. As it was, I had to sit separately from my mom and kids because the place was so crowded. It's a nice spot to visit for a special occasion but there's no way I'd go there regularly. (P.S. to owners of Time-Out Market, consider some type of signage near entrance that can help people make a decision about where to dine without elbow-wrestling through brunch crowds to see menu placards.)  EDIT: I feel the need to edit based on the response from T-O market. I agree with you that the food is high quality and I really have no complaints on that front. But again, I must demur and say the prices are still too high, regardless of whether or not a "best chef." There is a real disconnect between low-brow elements (e.g. standing in line to order from a counter, picking up your own food at the same counter when it's ready, fighting for seating during brunch hours, sitting at bench-style tables, seeing no one bussing tables so I ate my lunch surrounded by other people's lunch debris... and not just one person's; there were at least 5 plates full of half-eaten food stacked around me as I ate) VS high-brow food and service at high-end prices. Plus some of the portions were TINY. I also got a little annoyed that at each place we ordered from, it automatically asked us for the amount we would like to tip. Why are we tipping for picking up our own food? Are the people working behind the counter making minimum wage, or are they on "server wages" and rely on tips? Because if the latter, that's no good. I am happy to spend a lot of money on a food experience, but what you offer is good food but a bad experience. So the high prices are not justified, in my opinion.

Time Out market Boston is a must-visit destination for every foodie in Boston.  It may not serve the most traditional fares, but the market brings the most creative and innovative chefs into one place, producing incredible food from pizzas to dumplings, and everything in between. I can't recommend the Hummus toast enough or the broccoli and cheese gyoza which works so well despite what you might think at first.  The industrial chic interiors and long communal tables really gives it that cool hangout vibe while the terrace is perfect for those long summer days.  Time Out Boston is a great place to visit. If food is what you're after, then you're going to the right place.

Great concept, horrible execution. After dining in several other food halls in other cities (Grand Central Market in LA, etc), the Time Out Market in Boston is a major let down. The space has a hip aesthetic but the awful service and overpriced salty food makes it not worth it. I gave this place multiple tries from different vendors and have consistently had rude and unhappy servers and bartenders. It is very apparent that several of the servers are unhappy to be working there and it comes off aggressively to customers. From a bartender rudely DENYING my military ID (a federal form of identification), to serves aggressively asking “what do you want?” Save your time and go somewhere else where you will save money and have a better dining experience.

Dined here last night and had Ms. Clucks Deluxe Chicken and Dumpling Soup for $14. The soup was so salty that I almost returned it. Wound up eating just the noodles. Husband ordered the chicken sandwich, which fell apart after one bite. Our total bill was about $28. Had a much better meal at the place that serves Mediterranean food during a previous visit.  During both visits we found the place to be extremely loud. If you go, make sure you sit next to your dining partner if you want to speak with one another. Otherwise, you’ll be shouting into the wind.  Some other things you should know. You have to go to the bar to get a drink, even if it’s a bottle of water, which makes no sense to me. Why can’t you order a bottle of water at the stall where you’re ordering your food? Why wait in line twice?  Others have mentioned the pricing, which we found to be expensive for what you get. We just returned from Lisbon where we visited Time Out Lisbon, which was a completely different experience. Lots of options for reasonably priced food, which was good quality. Something for everyone and every price point. Not the case here. Doubtful we’ll return. Other great eating options right in the same neighborhood.  Advice to Time Out. You can keep the food quality high and have some reasonably priced options. Allow each vendor to sell water. Do something NOW about the noise level. You’ve invested a ton in getting this concept up and running. Surely you can invest a bit more to deal with the noise issue.
